# Project Rules: Chrome Extension (Manifest V3)

> Browser extension built with Chrome Manifest V3, TypeScript, and modern web APIs.

## Project Identity

- **Type**: Browser Extension
- **Language**: TypeScript
- **Manifest**: Chrome Manifest V3
- **Bundler**: Vite / Webpack
- **Testing**: Vitest + Chrome Extension Testing Library

---

## Coding Standards

### Naming Conventions

| Element | Convention | Example |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| Content scripts | kebab-case | `content-script.ts` |
| Background | camelCase | `serviceWorker.ts` |
| Popup/Options | PascalCase (components) | `Popup.tsx` |
| Message types | UPPER_SNAKE_CASE | `FETCH_PAGE_DATA` |
| Storage keys | camelCase | `userSettings` |

### File Organization

```
src/
├── background/       # Service worker (MV3)
│   └── serviceWorker.ts
├── content/          # Content scripts
│   └── content-script.ts
├── popup/            # Popup UI
│   ├── Popup.tsx
│   └── popup.css
├── options/          # Options page
├── types/            # Shared TypeScript types
├── utils/            # Shared utilities
└── manifest.json     # Extension manifest
```

---

## Critical Rules (🔴)

### Rule 1: ✅ Always use Manifest V3 patterns

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — MV2 background page (deprecated)
chrome.browserAction.onClicked.addListener(() => { ... });

// ✅ GOOD — MV3 service worker
chrome.action.onClicked.addListener((tab) => { ... });
```

### Rule 2: ❌ Never use `eval()` or inline scripts

```json
// ❌ BAD — CSP violation
"content_security_policy": "script-src 'unsafe-eval'"

// ✅ GOOD — strict CSP
"content_security_policy": {
  "extension_pages": "script-src 'self'; object-src 'self'"
}
```

### Rule 3: ✅ Always request minimum permissions

```json
// ❌ BAD — over-permissioned
"permissions": ["<all_urls>", "tabs", "storage", "cookies", "history"]

// ✅ GOOD — minimal permissions
"permissions": ["storage", "activeTab"],
"host_permissions": ["https://specific-site.com/*"]
```

---

## Important Guidelines (🟠)

- Use `chrome.storage.local` instead of `localStorage` in service workers
- Handle service worker lifecycle (it can be terminated at any time)
- Use message passing (`chrome.runtime.sendMessage`) for cross-context communication
- Always handle `chrome.runtime.lastError` in callbacks

---

## Code Smells to Avoid

| ❌ Smell | ✅ Instead Do |
|----------|--------------|
| Persistent background page | Use MV3 service worker |
| `localStorage` in service worker | `chrome.storage.local` |
| `XMLHttpRequest` | Use `fetch` API |
| Broad host permissions | Use `activeTab` + specific hosts |
| Untyped message passing | Define message type interfaces |
